> I like how generic this message is. We could in principle extend it
> with rate limits per plugin, informational messages per plugin,
> whatever makes sense later.

Yep, exactly. Rate limits were something that I had in mind, as was a
flag “`bool allow_all_plugins = 2;`” for general-purpose storage (e.g.,
if people run their own instances, they _might_ want that).

> A slightly different design might prepare us for that eventuality even
> better […]

A downside of `repeated PluginControl plugin_controls;` is that it
doesn’t admit distinguishing between an old server that doesn’t know
about `PluginControl`s and a server that is denying all uploads. If we
did that, then rolling back the server to a pre-`PluginControl` version
would be dangerous once we’d pushed a new uploader, so I like having the
wrapper message.

An `AllPluginControls` with repeated `SinglePluginControl`s does resolve
this, and indeed is more flexible along the plugin axis. But it’s a bit
less flexible on other axes: e.g., I could imagine wanting

```proto
message ServerInfoResponse {
  // ...
  PluginControl plugin_control = 4;
  repeated RateLimit rate_limit = 5;
}

message RateLimit {
  oneof what {
    // Rate-limit a specific plugin.
    string plugin_name = 1;
    // Rate-limit all data of a given data class.
    .tensorboard.DataClass data_class = 2;
  }
  // Send requests at most once every this often.
  Duration min_request_period = 3;
}
```

in which case the `SinglePluginControl`s aren’t obviously the right
place to put the rate limiting.

Given that both options seem reasonable and the worst-case costs aren’t
too high (we can either deprecate the old fields entirely, or use a
hybrid solution like denormalizing plugin names or using the plugin
control ordering as an index; neither is perfect, but they’re not
maintenance nightmares), I’m going to keep this as is, because this way
is simpler right now. Thank you for the suggestion!

My concern here would be that the storage of the configuration would become a lot more complex. Looking back at the [db schema PR](https://github.com/pulumi/pulumi-service/pull/4611/files), we then add the config_schema to the `Policies` table. Today we only use this table to display the Policies in the pack. 

A few things we would need to change:
* We would then need to query this table to do the schema validation on the front end.
* The `PolicyPackConfigs` would also need a `policy_name` column to reference the correct policy. (The `Policies` table PK is (`policy_pack_id`, `name`))
* For the `PolicyGroupPolicyPacks` and `ProgramUpdatePolicyPacks` things will become a lot more complex, since we will need to reference multiple `PolicyPackConfigs`
   * For both situations, we would likely need a second table to hold all the ids
   * Maybe the other option is to make a giant JSON document thats a map of `policy_name` to the configuration. In this case we could store each config_schema in the `Policies` table and then the configuration can still be stored in one entry of the `PolicyPackConfigs`. ---> But then in this case why couldnt we do something similar with the schema, where the schema isnt a proper JSON schema but instead a map of `policy_name` to JSON schema to use for that policy. This should allow you to have the same reference multiple times. 


```go
type CreatePolicyPackRequest struct {
	...
	// The JSON schema for the Policy Pack's configuration.
	ConfigSchemas map[string]*json.RawMessage `json:"configSchemas,omitempty"`
}
type PolicyConfigSchema struct {
	// Config property name to JSON Schema map.
	Properties: map[string]*json.RawMessage `json:"properties,omitempty"`
	// Required config properties.
	Required:   []string                   `json:"required,omitempty"`
}
