I presume this problem is about a readability, right?
I definitely can see why declaring `a`, `b`, and `c` is defined up in the closure and I can comprehend why this is a problem. If we are testing truly pure components, your way would be clean, but, for more complex stateful components, current pattern allows for composition that is a bit more powerful than setUp (you _can_ do composition with setUp but at that point, it is not that different from `beforeEach`). For instance,

```ts
describe('foo test', () => {
  beforeEach(() => {
    // global setUp
  });

  describe('feature A', () => {
    beforeEach(() => {
      // partial setUp or set some default values for mocks relevant for testing feature A
      // mock or setUp state a, b, c, d
    });

    describe('very complex thing that needs to be thoroughly tested', () => {
      beforeEach(() => {
        // more setUp for testing special case
        // update state c, d, e
      });

      it('case 1', () => {
        // change state a and e that are interesting for this spec
      })
      it('case 2', () => {...})
    });

    describe('another scenarios that require a lot of mocking', () => {
      beforeEach(() => {
        // more setUp for the second case
        // change b, d, e.
      });
    });
  });
});
```

I am not defending that this pattern is the best since there are numbers of times that I flipped through `beforeEach` which maybe the root of problem you are pointing at. However, given that other tests are written in mocha/jasmine way and given that composition definitely was nice, I am leaning towards not refactoring.

However, given that this component is not as stateful as Angular ones, I am willing to refactor this module into the pattern you are suggesting. Please let me know what you prefer.

@Irving-cl I believe there has been some confusion interpreting the specification and there should not be any aggregation of metrics when Enhanced ACK probing is configured. The spec states, for the contents of the IE in the ACK:

> The remaining 1 or 2 bytes contain the requested Link Metrics data assessed **for the acknowledged frame** in order of request.

This means there is no need to store aggregated information for every neighbor, just appending the metrics for every triggering 802.15.14-2015 frame should be enough.

